@dev Returns true if `account` is a contract.
 [IMPORTANT]
 ====
 It is unsafe to assume that an address for which this function returns
 false is an externally-owned account (EOA) and not a contract.
 Among others, `isContract` will return false for the following
 types of addresses:
  - an externally-owned account
  - a contract in construction
  - an address where a contract will be created
  - an address where a contract lived, but was destroyed
 ====

natspec.details: Implementation of Ocean datatokens Factory      DTFactory deploys datatoken proxy contracts.      New datatoken proxy contracts are links to the template contract's bytecode.      Proxy contract functionality is based on Ocean Protocol custom implementation of ERC1167 standard.

add721TokenTemplate(address).details: add a new NFT Template. Only Factory Owner can call it

addTokenTemplate(address).details: add a new ERC20Template. Only Factory Owner can call it

constructor.details: constructor      Called on contract deployment. Could not be called with zero address parameters.

params._template: refers to the address of a deployed datatoken contract.
params._template721: refers to the address of ERC721 template

createNftWithErc20((string,string,uint25.details: createNftWithErc20      Creates a new NFT, then a ERC20,all in one call

createNftWithErc20WithDispenser((string,.details: createNftWithErc20WithDispenser      Creates a new NFT, then a ERC20, then a Dispenser, all in one call      Use this carefully

createNftWithErc20WithFixedRate((string,.details: createNftWithErc20WithFixedRate      Creates a new NFT, then a ERC20, then a FixedRateExchange, all in one call      Use this carefully, because if Fixed Rate creation fails, you are still going to pay a lot of gas

createNftWithErc20WithPool((string,strin.details: createNftWithErc20WithPool      Creates a new NFT, then a ERC20, then a Pool, all in one call      Use this carefully, because if Pool creation fails, you are still going to pay a lot of gas

createNftWithMetaData((string,string,uin.details: createNftWithMetaData      Creates a new NFT, then sets the metadata, all in one call      Use this carefully

createToken(uint256,string[],address[],u.details: Deploys new datatoken proxy contract.      This function is not called directly from here. It's called from the NFT contract. An NFT contract can deploy multiple ERC20 tokens.

params.addresses: refers to an array of addresses                     [0]  = minter account who can mint datatokens (can have multiple minters)                     [1]  = paymentCollector  initial paymentCollector  for this DT                     [2]  = publishing Market Address                     [3]  = publishing Market Fee Token
params.bytess: refers to an array of bytes, not in use now, left for future templates
params.strings: refers to an array of strings                      [0] = name                      [1] = symbol
params.uints: refers to an array of uints                     [0] = cap_ the total ERC20 cap                     [1] = publishing Market Fee Amount

returns.token: address of a new proxy datatoken contract

params._templateIndex: template index we want to use
params.additionalERC20Deployer: if != address(0), we will add it with ERC20Deployer role
params.additionalMetaDataUpdater: if != address(0), we will add it with updateMetadata role
params.name: NFT name
params.transferable: if NFT is transferable. Cannot be changed afterwards

disable721TokenTemplate(uint256).details: disable an NFT Template. Only Factory Owner can call it

disableTokenTemplate(uint256).details: disable an ERC20Template. Only Factory Owner can call it

getCurrentTokenCount().details: get the current ERC20token deployed count.

owner().details: Returns the address of the current owner.

reactivate721TokenTemplate(uint256).details: reactivate a disabled NFT Template. Only Factory Owner can call it

reactivateTokenTemplate(uint256).details: reactivate a disabled ERC20Template. Only Factory Owner can call it

renounceOwnership().details: Leaves the contract without owner. It will not be possible to call `onlyOwner` functions anymore. Can only be called by the current owner. NOTE: Renouncing ownership will leave the contract without an owner, thereby removing any functionality that is only available to the owner.
